ast live on the Commissioner’s website and provide </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">her with </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an opportunity to examine areas of good and bad performance at a local, regional and national level. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The attached summary provides a breakdown of the different questions that have been asked under each of the priority areas. This approach has been commended by the Minister of State for Policing and Crime at the national ‘Police &amp; Crime Commissioners - One Year On’ event and also by HMIC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner also holds a quarterly meeting with the Chief Constable to discuss Professional Standards which includes complaints, gifts and hospitality in pursuance of s.15 (1) Police Reform Act 2002 and s.1 Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The role of police and crime panels in holding their commissioners to account</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner has established a professional and constructive working relationship with the Sussex Police &amp; Crime Panel</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, in adherence with the Policing Protocol Order 2011. Public questions are now asked at the Panel meetings to ensure greater transparency and the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Panel has commented favourably on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> both</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Commissioner’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Annual Report and Half Year Monitoring Report that has been received to date. The Panel have also established reference groups to look at the revision of the Police &amp; Crime Plan, the future for victim services and financial scrutiny. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ollowing the Stage 2 transfers under the Police reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and the Sussex Chief Constable have agreed and submitted a Stage 2 staff transfer proposal to the Home Secretary to take effect from April 2014. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ome Secretary has advised that the statutory Policing Protocol will be the benchmark against which a transfer scheme will be assessed and approved and has defined three key principles which should underpin local arrangements.  The scheme has been drawn up on this basis and the three key principles are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Maintaining the operational inde</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">pendence of the Chief Constable;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Upholding the Policing Protocol (which gives Police &amp; Crime Commissioners responsibility for the ‘totality of policing’ within their forc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e area);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Ensuring clearly defined roles and responsibilities (i.e. governance rests with the PCC whilst operational delivery sits with the Chief Constable).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n addition to the principles set by the Home Secretary, the C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ommissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and Chief Constable have worked on the basis of the following principles for the proposed Stage 2 arrangements for Sussex:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Despite the different roles and responsibilities, future working arrangements between the Force and C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ommissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> must be a joint endeavour, focused upon improving outcomes for local people as set out in the Police </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&amp; Crime Plan;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In times of diminishing resource, implementation of the transfer arrangements should be as cost effective as possible and the resulting structures must represent the best value for the public in Sussex</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Stage 2 transfer arrangements must, as far as is possible, minimise unnecessary change and upheaval for staff</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Chief Constable must remain operationally independent, be seen as a provider of services and have responsibility for those support services that assist with operational delivery</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ommissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> must ensure there is sufficient capacity and capability to undertake the statutory responsibilities (e.g. ensuring the efficiency and effectiveness of the Force and driving value for money improvements)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Collaborative opportunities, particularly those with Surrey, should not be impeded by the arrangements implemented for Stage 2.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span s