s in budget and precept setting</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner has a statutory obligation to set the police budget and is currently</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">seeking the views of Sussex taxpayers regarding the 2014/2015 precept.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Mrs Bourne fulfilled</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">her election pledge to freeze the precept during her first year of office and, as a result, residents have paid the same amount for policing in Sussex for the last four years.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Despite the enormous challenge set, Sussex Police</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is on track to achieve the savings required by 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, in order to meet emerging crime threats, the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Commissioner needs to consider the case to secure additional funding next year and is considering a precept rise of 3.6% for 2014/2015.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">has a precept consultation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">open </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">on her website and the same questions are being asked through the Sussex Police Local Neighbourhood Survey.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The HMIC Value for Money Profile 2013, confirms that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the Office of the Sussex Police &amp; Crime Commissioner has the lowest policing body cost nationally at £0.66 per population, in comparison to the national average of £1.26.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#454545; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Commissioner understands the local policing priorities </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in Sussex </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">which have influenced the four priority areas in her Police &amp; Crime Plan.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> This includes drawing extensively from public consultation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> surveys and the correspondence received by the office.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Mrs Bourne regularly takes part in Question &amp; Answer webcasts which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are available live on the Commissioner’s website and provide members of the public with an opportunity to ask questions and receive answers from the Commissioner directly. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Sussex is made up of two C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ounty </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Councils and one U</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">nitary </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">uthority, which covers 12 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">District Councils plus</